commitResults.messageTitle: Implement assert feature to document important assumptions in code
commitResults.messageBody:
The code now includes assertions to check for critical assumptions at various points. These assertions validate important preconditions, such as ensuring non-null inputs, valid indices, and properly initialized objects. Additionally, assertions document control-flow and class invariants, such as ensuring that certain values remain within expected ranges.

This change enhances the robustness of the code by helping catch potential issues early during development. Assertions are not intended for normal error handling and will be disabled in production builds for performance reasons.
Add assertions to check critical assumptions

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor Parser class to eliminate arrowhead anti-pattern
commitResults.messageBody:
Refactored the `parseDateTime` method in the `Parser` class to remove
nested try-catch blocks and avoid the arrowhead anti-pattern.
This improves code readability and maintainability by reducing
deep nesting and simplifying the control flow.

The refactoring maintains the functionality of parsing date strings
using multiple predefined formats, ensuring invalid inputs are
handled appropriately and providing feedback for invalid formats.
Refactor Parser class to eliminate arrowhead anti-pattern

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor Parser class to use Streams for date parsing
commitResults.messageBody:
Refactored the `parseDateTime` method in the `Parser` class to utilize
Java Streams for cleaner and more efficient code. Streams are now
used to attempt parsing with various date and time formats, and
Optional is returned to handle success or failure gracefully.

This approach reduces nested if-else statements (arrowhead code)
and enhances readability and maintainability of the code. DateTime
and Date parsing functions have been separated for better structure.
Refactor Parser class to use Streams for date parsing

commitResults.messageTitle: Set up Continuous Integration with GitHub Actions
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit adds GitHub Actions for continuous integration. The workflow is
configured to run tests automatically on each push to the repository. This
ensures that code changes meet quality standards before being merged.

CI tasks include:
- Compiling the codebase.
- Running the unit tests.
- Reporting test results for feedback.

With this setup, the team will benefit from automatic validation of code
before it is merged, ensuring higher code quality and reducing potential
issues.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor Ui class to align with Buu's personality
commitResults.messageBody:
The Ui class messages previously included references to tasks as candy,
which was inconsistent with the intended task-focused behavior.
Additionally, the chatbot's personality did not fully align with Buu's
playful and energetic character from the anime.

Refactor the Ui class to remove candy references and update messages to
better reflect Buuâ€™s personality. This ensures that the chatbot remains
fun and engaging while staying focused on task management.

commitResults.messageTitle: This commit enhances the code to handle various anticipated errors during product usage. Improved error handling will provide users with clearer feedback and prevent unexpected crashes.
commitResults.messageBody:
Handled errors include:
- Command format errors such as extra spaces, missing or duplicate
  parameters, and unexpected special characters.
- Environment issues such as missing or inaccessible files and invalid
  file content.
- Data validation errors like start date/time later than end date/time,
  duplicated values where uniqueness is expected, and invalid dates.

These improvements ensure more robust error handling, improving user
experience and reducing the likelihood of incorrect program behavior.

commitResults.messageTitle: SetPriorityCommand: ensure task index validation and throw exception
commitResults.messageBody:
The SetPriorityCommand class did not throw an exception when
the task index was out of bounds, leading to test failures for
invalid task index scenarios.

This behavior caused an inconsistency when invalid input was provided,
as errors were displayed via the UI but not
properly handled in the code.

Let's throw an IllegalArgumentException when the task index
is out of bounds in the execute() method. This will ensure that
invalid input is properly handled and the corresponding
test cases pass.

This change improves the robustness of task index validation and ensures
better error handling for out-of-range task indices.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add final touch-up and ensure all functions are tested thoroughly
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit finalizes the testing by adding comprehensive test coverage
for all functions in the project. The test cases ensure correct
behavior for edge cases, valid inputs, and invalid inputs across
all commands and functions.

Key changes include:
- Added missing test cases for boundary conditions.
- Enhanced existing test cases to handle edge cases.
- Verified that error handling works correctly for all scenarios.
- Ensured that the task index validation and priority setting logic are
  thoroughly tested, including out-of-bounds inputs.

These changes guarantee that all functions are working correctly
and improve the robustness and reliability of the project.
